[[File:<U+0420><U+0438><U+0441>.0.jpg|280px|thumb|alt=Photograph of the Sayano-Shusenskaya Dam. |[[Sayano<U+2013>Shushenskaya Dam]], the largest [[hydropower plant]] of Russia]]

'''Renewable energy in Russia''' mainly consists of hydroelectric energy. The country is the [[List of countries by electricity production from renewable sources|fifth largest producer of renewable energy]] in the world, although it is 56th when hydroelectric energy is not taken into account.<ref name="Windfair">{{cite web|author=Trevor Sievert|title=Russia- Russian Wind Power| publisher = Industry News| date = 23 July 2010 | url = http://www.windfair.net/press/7726.html| accessdate = 25 February 2011}}</ref> Only 179&nbsp;TWh of Russia's energy production comes from renewable energy sources, out of a total economically feasible potential of 1823&nbsp;TWh.<ref name="NEFCO_Energy">{{cite web|author=Raili Kajaste|title=NEFCO Renewable Energy Projects in Russia| publisher = NEFCO| date = 23 October 2008 | url = http://www.nefco.org/files/NEFCO_Kajaste_MOW_23%20Oct08.pdf| accessdate = 26 February 2011}}</ref> Only 16% of [[Russia]]'s [[electricity]] is generated from [[hydropower]], and less than 1% is generated from all other [[renewable energy]] sources combined. Roughly 68% of Russia's electricity is generated from [[thermal power]] and 16% from [[nuclear power]].<ref name="EIA1">{{cite web|title=Russia- Electrity| publisher = U.S. Energy Information Administration| date = November 2010 | url = http://www.eia.doe.gov/cabs/Russia/Electricity.html| accessdate = 23 January 2011}}</ref> The abundance of [[fossil fuel]]s in the Soviet Union and the Russian Federation has resulted in little development of the renewable energy sector. There are currently plans to expand the share of renewable energy in Russia's energy output, plans strongly encouraged by the Russian government.<ref name="RT_Business">{{cite web|author=Anastasia Kostomarova, James Blake|title=Russian renewable energy prepares for a bigger slice of the power pie| publisher = Business RT| date = 25 August 2009 | url = http://rt.com/business/news/russian-renewable-energy-potential/| accessdate = 23 January 2011}}</ref> Russian President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] has called for renewable energy to have a larger share of Russia's energy output, and has taken steps to promote the development of renewable energy in Russia since 2008.<ref name="RIAN">{{cite web|author=Mikhail Klementiev|title=Medvedev orders incentives for renewable energy use| publisher = RIA Novosti| date = 27 May 2010 | url = http://en.rian.ru/russia/20100527/159185774.html| accessdate = 23 January 2011}}</ref>

==History==
[[File:<U+0421><U+0442><U+0430><U+043B><U+0438><U+043D><U+0433><U+0440><U+0430><U+0434><U+0441><U+043A><U+0430><U+044F> <U+0413><U+042D><U+0421>.jpg|240px|thumb|left|alt=Postmark commemorating the Stalingrad Hydroelectric Power Station|In the [[Soviet Union]], large hydropower plants were among the [[Great construction projects of communism]] ([[Volga Hydroelectric Station|Stalingrad/Volgograd Hydroelectric Station]] pictured)]]
Most sources of renewable energy are new to Russia and have experienced development in recent years. However, hydroelectric power has a long history in Russia, dating back to the Soviet era. The rapid expansion of hydroelectric power in the Soviet Union began in 1930, when the total installed capacity equaled 600,000&nbsp;kWh. The Soviet Union built its first windmill in 1941, which had a capacity of 100&nbsp;kW.<ref name="Energy_Congress">{{cite web|title=Renewables: The Energy for the 21st Century| publisher = World Renewable Energy Congress VI| date = 1<U+2013>7 July 2000 | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=tl30wipZ-SoC&pg=PA2560&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate = 25 February 2011}}</ref> By the time the Soviet Union collapsed in 1990, it had a total installed capacity of {{nowrap|65 million kWh}}. The largest dams that Russia currently has, including the [[Sayano<U+2013>Shushenskaya Dam]], were built in the 1950s and 1960s.<ref name="RusHydro">{{cite web|title=Hydropower in Russia| publisher = RusHydro| date = 2008<U+2013>2009 | url = http://www.eng.rushydro.ru/industry/history| accessdate = 28 January 2011}}</ref> From the 1970s to 2000, the Soviet Union and Russia focused mainly on "traditional" power sources: thermal-, hydro- and nuclear power.<ref name="Energy_Congress" /> However, in 1986, the Soviet government announced new energy goals, which included further hydroelectric plant construction as well as the start of small-scale solar and wind use for electricity production. Overall, [[Energy policy of the Soviet Union|Soviet energy policy]] focused on nuclear and thermal power, although renewable energy was not completely neglected. The [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] prevented those goals from being fulfilled.<ref name="Soviet_Energy_Goals">{{cite web|title=Soviet Union- Energy Planning Goals| publisher = country-data.com| date = May 1989 | url = http://www.country-data.com/cgi-bin/query/r-12738.html| accessdate = 30 January 2011}}</ref>

The construction of the large dams prominent in Soviet times largely ended in the 1990s with the creation of the Russian Federation. In addition, due to the post-Soviet recession, much of the country's infrastructure, including dams, fell into disrepair.<ref name="RusHydro" /><ref name="Soviet_Infrastructure">{{cite web|author=Andrew Kramer|title=Decaying Soviet Infrastructure Shows Its Era| publisher = The New York Times| date = 20 August 2009 | url = http://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/21/business/global/21ruble.html| accessdate = 30 January 2011}}</ref> Use of oil and gas for energy took priority in Russia and renewable energy was ignored. This policy lasted until 2008, when Medvedev announced reforms to Russia's energy policies in an attempt to focus more on renewable energy. Since then, there has been rapid development of new renewable energy sources.<ref name="PE_Efficiency">{{cite web|author=David Amstell|title=Russian Energy efficiency: Medvedev's new favourite topic?| publisher = PE Power & Energy| date = 10 December 2009 | url = http://www.ngpowereu.com/news/russian-energy-efficiency/| accessdate = 30 January 2011}}</ref>

==Current status==
{{main|Energy in Russia}}
[[File:Russia electricity production by source pie.PNG|thumb|240px|alt=Pie graph detailing distribution of Russian electricity generation by source|Russia's electricity generation by source, 2008. [[Hydroelectricity]] had a 16% share that year, while other types of renewable sources accounted for less than 1%.]] 
Russia is one of the world's largest producers of energy, most of which it obtains from [[petroleum|oil]], [[natural gas]] and [[coal]]. The country's focus on those resources for production and export, which constitute 80% of foreign trade earnings, means it has paid little attention to renewable energy. Out of the 203&nbsp;GW of electric generation capacity that Russia has, 44&nbsp;GW comes from hydroelectricity, 307&nbsp;MW from [[geothermal energy|geothermal]], 15&nbsp;MW from [[wind power|wind]] and negligible amounts from other renewable sources.<ref name="GENI">{{cite web|title=Russia <U+2013> Grid Summary| publisher = Global Energy Network Institute| year = 2010 | url = http://www.geni.org/globalenergy/library/national_energy_grid/russia/index.shtml| accessdate = 23 January 2011}}</ref><ref name="Energy_survey">{{cite web|title=2007 Survey of Energy Resources| publisher = World Energy Council 2007| year = 2007 | url = http://www.worldenergy.org/documents/ser2007_final_online_version_1.pdf| accessdate = 23 January 2011}}</ref> In 2009, the Russian energy industry generated a total 992&nbsp;TWh of electricity, 176&nbsp;TWh of which was produced by hydroelectric power stations.<ref name="gks_electricity">{{cite web|url=http://www.gks.ru/bgd/regl/b10_12/IssWWW.exe/Stg/d02/14-24.htm|title=14.24. BASIC INDICATORS OF ORGANISATIONS BY KIND OF ECONOMIC ACTIVITIES <U+2013> "PRODUCTION AND SUPPLY OF ELECTRICITY, GAS AND WATER"|publisher=<U+0424><U+0435><U+0434><U+0435><U+0440><U+0430><U+043B><U+044C><U+043D><U+0430><U+044F> <U+0441><U+043B><U+0443><U+0436><U+0431><U+0430> <U+0433><U+043E><U+0441><U+0443><U+0434><U+0430><U+0440><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+0435><U+043D><U+043D><U+043E><U+0439> <U+0441><U+0442><U+0430><U+0442><U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+0438><U+043A><U+0438>|date=2010}}</ref> Some of Russia's hydroelectric power plants are outdated and are in need of additional investment, as shown by the [[2009 Sayano-Shushenskaya hydro accident|accident at the Sayano-Shushenskaya HPP]] in 2009.<ref name="Windfair" />

President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] announced in May 2010 that the Russian government would strongly consider purchasing electricity generated from renewable energy sources in an attempt to encourage development of renewable energy. The government has plans for 4.5% of Russia's energy output to come from non-hydroelectric renewable energy sources.<ref name="RIAN" /> Additionally, in November 2010, the government approved a US$300&nbsp;billion program to make factories and buildings more [[efficient energy use|energy efficient]]; it also announced plans to construct eight energy-efficient lamp production plants, promote [[recycling]] and support the construction of a [[Hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid car]] plant. Medvedev announced in late 2009 that he wanted to cut Russian energy consumption by 40% by 2020.<ref name="PE_Efficiency" /><ref name="BWE_Efficiency">{{cite web|author= Rachel Morarjee|title=Red to green: Russia begins energy saving| publisher = Business New Europe | date = 18 November 2010 | url = http://rbth.ru/articles/2010/11/18/red_to_green_russia_begins_energy_saving05128.html| accessdate = 29 January 2011}}</ref> At the moment, development is slowed by low investment, economic instability, low public demand and low tariffs on heat and electricity.<ref name="EBRD">{{cite web|title=Russia| publisher = European Bank for Reconstruction and Development| year = 2010 | url = http://www.ebrdrenewables.com/sites/renew/countries/Russia/default.aspx| accessdate = 23 January 2011}}</ref> Subsidies for natural gas are another obstacle to renewable energy development.<ref name="Ashgate_Energy">{{cite web|author= Indrea Overland, Heidi Kjaernet|title=Russian Renewable Energy <U+2013> The Potential for International Cooperation| publisher = Ashgate Publishing Ltd| year = 2009 | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=nlPoyKVND2wC&pg=PA77&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate = 25 February 2011}}</ref>

== Hydropower ==
[[File:Pavodok, Zhigulevskaya GES.JPG|240px|thumb|left|alt=refer to caption|[[Zhiguli Hydroelectric Station]] during a [[freshet]]]]
Hydropower is the most used form of renewable energy in Russia, and there is large potential in Russia for more use of hydropower. Russia has 102 hydropower plants with capacities of over 100&nbsp;MW, making it fifth in the world for hydropower production. It is also second in the world for hydro potential, yet only 20% of this potential is developed.<ref name="RusHydro" /> Russia is home to 9% of the world's hydro resources ,<ref name="EBRD" /> mostly in Siberia and the country's far east. At the end of 2005, the generating capacity from [[hydroelectricity|hydroelectric]] sources in Russia was 45,700&nbsp;MW, and an additional 5,648&nbsp;MW was under construction. Russia has much potential for using its hydro resources, with a theoretical potential of about 2,295&nbsp;TWh/yr, with 852&nbsp;TWh being economically feasible.<ref name="Energy_survey" />

The largest dams in Russia are the [[Sayano-Shushenskaya Dam]], which has an installed capacity of 6,400&nbsp;MW; the [[Krasnoyarsk Dam]] (6,000&nbsp;MW); the [[Bratsk Hydroelectric Power Station|Bratsk Dam]] (4,500&nbsp;MW); the [[Ust-Ilimsk Hydroelectric Power Station|Ust-Ilimsk Dam]] (4,320&nbsp;MW) and the [[Zeya Dam]] (1,330&nbsp;MW).<ref name="RusHydro" /> Some of the most recent dam projects are the [[Bureya Dam]] (2010&nbsp;MW) and the [[Irganai Dam]] (800&nbsp;MW). The [[Boguchany Dam]] (1920&nbsp;MW), Zelenchuk Dam (320&nbsp;MW), Zaramag Dam (352&nbsp;MW) and Nizhne-Chereksky (60&nbsp;MW) are currently under construction.<ref name="Energy_survey" /> [[RusHydro]] is the largest hydroelectric company in Russia and the second largest hydroelectric producer in the world.<ref name="RusHydro_Reuters">{{cite web|title=Russia appoints Sechin ally to manage hydro giant| publisher = Reuters| date = 23 November 2009 | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/2009/11/23/rushydro-dod-idUKGEE5AM0RW20091123?sp=true| accessdate = 30 January 2011}}</ref> In October 2010, [[China Yangtze Power]], the largest hydropower corporation in China, and [[EuroSibEnergo]], a Russian energy company, signed a cooperation agreement to expand hydroelectric energy production in Russia and export energy to China's northern territories.<ref name="China_Hydro">{{cite web|title=Russia's EuroSibEnergo signs deal with China's hydro power corporation| publisher = RIA Novosti| date = 2 December 2010 | url = http://www.bsr-russia.com/en/power-a-utilities/item/1307-russias-eurosibenergo-signs-deal-with-chinas-hydro-power-corporation.html| accessdate = 26 February 2011}}</ref> The [[West Siberian Generating Company]] has plans to start construction of eight mini-hydroelectric power plants in the Altai region before 2015.<ref name="West_Siberian">{{cite web|title=West Siberian genco to build 8 hydro-electric plants in Altai| publisher = RIA Novosti| date = 15 December 2010 | url = http://en.rian.ru/russia/20101215/161783545.html| accessdate = 26 February 2011}}</ref>

== Geothermal energy ==
{{main|Geothermal power in Russia}}
Geothermal energy is the second most used form of renewable energy in Russia but represents less than 1% of the total energy production. The first geothermal power plant in Russia was built at Pauzhetka, [[Kamchatka_Peninsula|Kamchatka]], in 1966, with a capacity of 5&nbsp;MW. The total geothermal installed capacity in 2005 was 79&nbsp;MW, with 50&nbsp;MW coming from a plant at Verkhne-Mutnovsky. Russia is currently developing a 100&nbsp;MW plant at Mutnovsky and a 50&nbsp;MW plant in [[Kaliningrad]].<ref name="Energy_survey" /> Most geothermal resources are currently used for heating settlements in the [[North Caucasus]] and [[Kamchatka Peninsula|Kamchatka]]. Half of the geothermal production is used to heat homes and industrial buildings, one third is used to heat greenhouses and 13% is used for industrial processes.<ref name="IGC">{{cite web|author=Valentina Svalova|title=Geothermal energy use in Russia| publisher = International Geothermal Conference| date = September 2003 | url = http://www.jardhitafelag.is/media/PDF/S10Paper085.pdf| accessdate = 23 January 2011}}</ref>

In October 2010, [[Sergei Shmatko]], Russia's energy minister, stated that Russia and Iceland would work together to develop Kamchatka's geothermal energy sources.<ref name="Iceland_Geothermal">{{cite web|title=Russia, Iceland to tap geothermal energy sources: minister | publisher = China Daily| date = 26 October 2010 | url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/xinhua/2010-10-26/content_1075651.html | accessdate = 25 February 2011}}</ref> Russia is also investigating foreign investment possibilities for developing geothermal energy in the [[Kuril Islands]].<ref name="Kuril_Geothermal">{{cite web|title=Moscow ready to offer breaks to foreign investors on Kurils| publisher = RIA Novosti| date = 11 February 2011 | url = http://en.rian.ru/russia/20110211/162556520.html | accessdate = 6 March 2011}}</ref>

== Solar energy ==
Solar energy is virtually nonexistent in Russia, despite its large potential in the country. The first Russian [[solar plant]] was opened in [[Belgorod Oblast]] in November 2010.<ref name="Newsland_solar">{{cite web|title=The first solar power plant has been constructed in Russia| publisher = Newsland| date = 13 November 2010 | url = http://www.newsland.ru/News/Detail/id/585927/cat/69/| accessdate = 15 March 2011}}</ref> Russia has a total theoretical potential of 2,213&nbsp;TWh/yr for solar energy, with an economically feasible amount of 101&nbsp;TWh. The southern parts of Russia, especially the North Caucasus, have the greatest potential for solar energy.<ref name=Energy_survey/> Russia plans to set up an overall solar capacity of 150&nbsp;MW by 2020.<ref name="Sunless_Russia">{{cite web|title=Sunless Russia seeks more solar energy| publisher = International Business Times| date = 8 October 2010 | url = http://www.ibtimes.com/articles/70035/20101008/sunless-russia-seeks-more-solar-energy.htm| accessdate = 30 January 2011}}</ref> 

Plans for the construction of a new solar plant on the [[Black Sea]] have been announced and the plant is expected to begin operations by 2012. This plant, which will have a capacity of 12.3&nbsp;MW, is being built by [[Russian Nanotechnology Corporation|Rusnano]] and [[Renova Group|Renova]].<ref name="POWER-GEN">{{cite web|title=Russia to build first solar power plant| publisher = Power-GEN Worldwide| date = 3 November 2010 | url = http://www.powergenworldwide.com/index/display/articledisplay/4371476976/articles/powergenworldwide/renewables/solar/2010/11/russia-to_build_first.html| accessdate = 23 January 2011}}</ref> Solar Wind LLC and Rusnano are building a plant that will produce double-sided solar panels, which will be able to collect solar energy from both sides. Construction is expected to finish in early 2011 and the plant will have an annual manufacturing capacity of 30&nbsp;MW.<ref name=Sunless_Russia/> [[Nitol Solar]] is the largest Russian company in the area of scientific development and manufacture of products used to generate solar energy.<ref name="Spiegel_Solar">{{cite web|author=Jason Bush|title=Nitol, Russia's Emerging Solar Power Star| publisher = Spiegel Online International| date = 14 July 2009 | url = http://www.spiegel.de/international/business/0,1518,636165,00.html| accessdate = 21 February 2011}}</ref> Russia and India are currently discussing the possibility of a joint venture to produce [[Wafer (electronics)|silicon wafers]] for the creation of [[photovoltaics|photovoltaic]] cells.<ref name="Kuril_Geothermal">{{cite web|title=India, Russia exploring JV in solar photo-voltaic cells| publisher = Russia & India Report| date = 21 February 2011 | url = http://indrus.in/articles/2011/02/21/india_russia_exploring_jv_in_solar_photo-voltaic_cells_12191.html| accessdate = 6 March 2011}}</ref>

== Wind energy ==
[[File:Wind turbine in Omni Hotel Murmansk.jpg|160px|thumb|alt=refer to caption|Wind turbine near an [[Omni Hotels & Resorts|Omni Hotel]], [[Murmansk]]. The wind power potential of [[Murmansk Oblast]] is one of the largest among Russian regions.]]
Russia has a long history of small-scale wind energy use but has never developed large-scale commercial wind energy production. Most of its current wind production is located in agricultural areas with low population densities where connection to the main energy grid is difficult. Russia is estimated to have a total potential of 80,000 TWh/yr for wind energy, 6,218&nbsp;TWh/yr of which is economically feasible.<ref name="Energy_survey" /> Most of this potential is found in the southern steppes and the seacoasts of Russia, although in many of these areas the population density is less than {{nowrap|1 person per square km}}. This low population density means that there is little existing electricity infrastructure currently in place, which hinders development of these resources.<ref name="Energy_Congress" />  In 2006, Russia had a total installed wind capacity of 15&nbsp;MW.<ref name="RIAN2">{{cite web|title=Russia to spend $200 million on largest wind-power plant| publisher = RIA Novosti| date = 30 July 2010 | url = http://en.rian.ru/russia/20100730/160006679.html| accessdate = 23 January 2011}}</ref> Current Russian wind energy projects have a combined capacity of over 1,700&nbsp;MW. The Russian Wind Energy Association predicts that if Russia achieves its goal of having 4.5% of its energy come from renewable sources by 2020, the country will have a total wind capacity of 7&nbsp;GW.<ref name="Siemens_WindE">{{cite web|author=Honey Garcia|title=Siemens makes a bid for Russia<U+2019>s wind power through joint venture| publisher = Ecoseed| date = 16 July 2011 | url = http://www.ecoseed.org/en/wind-energy/other-wind-technologies/article/58-other-wind-technologies/7606-siemens-makes-a-bid-for-russia%E2%80%99s-wind-power-through-joint-venture| accessdate = 6 March 2011}}</ref>

In 2010, plans for the construction of a wind power plant in [[Yeisk]], on the [[Sea of Azov]], were announced. It is expected to initially have a capacity of 50&nbsp;MW, which will become 100&nbsp;MW a year later.<ref name="RIAN2" /> German engineering company [[Siemens]] announced in July 2010, following a visit to Russia by Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]], that it would build wind power plants in Russia.<ref name="Windfair" /> By 2015, the company hopes to install 1,250&nbsp;MW of capacity in Russia.<ref name="Siemens_WindE" />

== Tidal energy ==
[[File:Okhotsk-Japan5PZG.png|thumb|left|240px|alt=Map showing the location of the Penzhin Bay|[[Penzhin Bay]] is the location of the proposed [[Penzhin Tidal Power Plant]], which could become the world's largest electric power station.]]
Russia has many tidal energy resources at its disposal, although they are currently underdeveloped as well. The [[Kola Bay]] and [[Sea of Okhotsk]] alone could produce 100&nbsp;GW with tidal power stations, and the national energy potential from tidal energy can compete with current total energy production.<ref name="RIC">{{cite web|title=Russian power plants soon to utilize tidal energy| publisher = Russia InfoCentre| date = 24 June 2005 | url = http://www.russia-ic.com/news/show/929| accessdate = 23 January 2011}}</ref> The currently active [[Kislaya Guba Tidal Power Station]] is the largest tidal power facility in Russia and has the [[List of tidal power stations|fourth largest capacity]] (1.7&nbsp;MW) among the world's [[tidal power plant]]s.<ref name="Gorlov_Tidal">{{cite web|author=A. M. Gorlov|title=Tidal Energy| publisher = Northeastern University| year = 2001 | url = http://www.gcktechnology.com/GCK/Images/ms0032%20final.pdf| accessdate = 23 January 2011}}</ref>

Plans for constructing an 800&nbsp;MW tidal power plant in the [[Barents Sea]] were announced in 2008.<ref name="BO">{{cite web|title=Tidal power for northernmost Russia| publisher = Barnets Observer| date = 2 June 2008 | url = http://www.barentsobserver.com/tidal-power-for-northernmost-russia.4487346-16149.html| accessdate = 23 January 2011}}</ref> Possible long-term projects include the [[Penzhin Tidal Power Plant]], which could become the largest power station in the world, with an installed capacity of up to 87&nbsp;[[Watt|GW]] and an annual production of 200&nbsp;[[watt-hour|TWh]].<ref>{{cite conference
| url         = http://h2forum2008.ru/docs/pdf/abstracts/5_3_21.pdf
| title       = <U+041F><U+0440><U+0438><U+043B><U+0438><U+0432><U+043D><U+044B><U+0435> <U+044D><U+043B><U+0435><U+043A><U+0442><U+0440><U+043E><U+0441><U+0442><U+0430><U+043D><U+0446><U+0438><U+0438> (<U+041F><U+042D><U+0421>) <U+2014> <U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+043E><U+0447><U+043D><U+0438><U+043A> <U+044D><U+043D><U+0435><U+0440><U+0433><U+0438><U+0438>, <U+0437><U+0430><U+043F><U+0430><U+0441><U+0430><U+0435><U+043C><U+044B><U+0439> <U+0432> <U+0432><U+043E><U+0434><U+043E><U+0440><U+043E><U+0434><U+0435>
