==Biofuel==
Russia's [[biofuel]] industry is new, but it has been developing rapidly in recent years. Russia is one of the largest grain producers, has a well-developed [[ethanol|ethyl alcohol]] industry and has increasing [[Brassica napus|rapeseed]] (often used to create [[biodiesel]]) production rates.<ref name="APEC_Biofuel">{{cite web|title=Russia Biofuels Activities| publisher = Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation| year = 2008 | url = http://www.biofuels.apec.org/me_russia.html| accessdate = 28 January 2011}}</ref> The Russian government declared in 2008 that it would play an active role in developing the biofuel industry by building 30 new biofuel plants and providing tax breaks and subsidized interest rates to biofuel energy projects.<ref name="Modern_Russia">{{cite web|title=Russia's biofuel energy revolution| publisher = Modern Russia| date = 22 November 2010 | url = http://www.modernrussia.com/content/russia%E2%80%99s-biofuel-energy-revolution| accessdate = 28 January 2011}}</ref> Although these plans were delayed, on 13 September 2010, Medvedev announced that construction would begin in early 2011.<ref name="Geographical_Society">{{cite web|title=First Biofuel Plant to be built in Russia| publisher = Russian Geographical Society| date = 19 October 2010 | url = http://int.rgo.ru/news/first-biofuel-plant-to-be-built-in-russia/| accessdate = 28 January 2011}}</ref> [[Butanol fuel|Biobutanol]], the biofuel produced by these plants, would be produced from [[lumber|timber]] by-products, such as [[woodchips]] and [[sawdust]].<ref name="APEC_Biofuel" /><ref name="Modern_Russia" /><ref name="Gazeta_Biofuel">{{cite web|title=Russia's first biofuel plant| publisher = Rossiyskaya Gazeta| date = 6 October 2010 | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sponsored/russianow/business/8045849/Russias-first-biofuel-plant.html| accessdate = 28 January 2011}}</ref>

[[File:Shatura steam power plant (2010).jpg|thumb|right|240px|alt=Photograph of the Shatura Power Station|[[Shatura Power Station]] has the largest [[List of peat power stations|peat power]] capacity in the world]]
[[Lada]], a Russian car manufacturer, produced its first biofuel-powered automobile in November 2010. Deputy Transportation Minister Valery Okulov stated that Russian companies are currently developing helicopters that run on biofuel.<ref name="Modern_Russia" /> Russia hopes to export biofuel to the [[European Union]];<ref name="RIAN_Biofuel">{{cite web|title=Russia wants to export biofuels and game to EU| publisher = RIA Novosti| date = 6 September 2010 | url = http://en.rian.ru/business/20100906/160488233.html| accessdate = 28 January 2011}}</ref> the country's Biotechnology Corporation estimates that Russia is capable of exporting {{nowrap|40 million tons}} of biofuel annually.<ref name="RNCOS_Biofuel">{{cite web|title=Russian Biofuel Industry Set to Reign European Market| publisher = RNCOS Industry Research Solutions| date = 18 May 2009 | url = http://www.rncos.com/Blog/2009/05/Russian-Biofuel-Industry-Set-to-Reign-European-Market.html| accessdate = 30 January 2011}}</ref>

==Biomass==
[[Biomass]] is already used in some parts of Russia to provide a total of 1%, or 9&nbsp;Twh/year, of Russia's total energy. However, due to Russia's vast forest and [[peat]] reserves,<ref group=nb>[[Peat]] is not universally recognized as [[renewable resource|renewable]] [[biomass]] resource, due to its long regeneration period.</ref> it has a total biomass technical potential of 431&nbsp;Twh/year, of which 285&nbsp;Twh/year is economically feasible.<ref name="IEA_Biomass">{{cite web|author=Elena Douraeva|title=Opportunities for Renewable Energy in Russia| publisher = International Energy Agency| year=2003 | url = http://www.iea.org/speech/2006/emb_renew.pdf| accessdate = 29 January 2011}}</ref><ref name="FFRI_Wood">{{cite web|author=Timo Karjalainen, Yuri Gerasimov|title=Energy Wood Potential in Northwest Russia| publisher = Finnish Forest Research Institute| date = September 2008 | url = http://www.biomassenergycentre.org.uk/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/RESOURCES/REF_LIB_RES/PUBLICATIONS/IEA_CONFERENCE/TIMO%20KARJALAINEN.PDF| accessdate = 29 January 2011}}</ref> Most of this potential is found in northwestern Russia, which has a developed [[Pulp (paper)|pulp]] and [[paper]] industry that can provide wood-based waste to use as biomass energy.<ref name="Our_Planet">{{cite web|author=Elena Merle-Beral|title=Waking the Giant| publisher = Our Planet | url = http://www.unep.org/ourplanet/imgversn/164/Elena%20Merle-Beral.pdf| accessdate = 29 January 2011}}</ref> 

Use of peat for energy production was prominent during the Soviet Union, with the peak occurring in 1965 and declining from that point. In 1929, over 40% of the Soviet Union's electric energy came from peat, which dropped to 1% by 1980. Currently, Russia is responsible for 17% of the world's peat production, and 20% of the peat that it produces, {{nowrap|1.5 million tons}}, is used for energy purposes.<ref name=Energy_survey/><ref name="RGS_Peat">{{cite web|title=Peat: Useful Resource or Hazard?| publisher = Russian Geographical Society| date=10 August 2010 | url = http://int.rgo.ru/news/peat-useful-resource-or-hazard/| accessdate = 29 January 2011}}</ref> [[Shatura Power Station]] in [[Moscow Oblast]] and Kirov Power Station in [[Kirov Oblast]] are the two [[List of peat power stations|largest peat power stations]] in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shatura Power Station|publisher=The Fourth Generation Company of the Wholesale Electricity Market|year=2007|url=http://eng.ogk-4.ru/?obj=about1|accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Russia's peat generation|publisher=The Milwaukee Journal|date=20 March 1959|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LlsaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=aiYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3107%2C5220455|accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref>

